00:08:17.530 --> 00:08:18.740
And this right here
is the colon cancer?

00:08:18.740 --> 00:08:19.450
DAVID AGUS: Exactly.

00:08:19.450 --> 00:08:19.790
SALMAN KHAN: OK.

00:08:19.790 --> 00:08:21.490
DAVID AGUS: And so
any pathologist would

00:08:21.490 --> 00:08:24.156
look under a microscope and they
would make a diagnosis and say,

00:08:24.156 --> 00:08:27.500
hey, this looks like colon
cancer gone to the lymph.

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:29.050
And in the bottom
is a different way

00:08:29.050 --> 00:08:32.030
of looking at cancer,
which is a CAT scan.

00:08:32.030 --> 00:08:34.679
So this is basically a
three-dimensional X-ray.

00:08:34.679 --> 00:08:36.400
I took a slice
right in the middle

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:40.030
that person's body and those
translucent areas in the middle

00:08:40.030 --> 00:08:42.030
there are colon
cancer metastasis.

00:08:42.030 --> 00:08:42.780
SALMAN KHAN: This?

00:08:42.780 --> 00:08:44.280
DAVID AGUS: Those
darker areas, yes.

00:08:44.280 --> 00:08:45.427
SALMAN KHAN: OK.

00:08:45.427 --> 00:08:47.010
DAVID AGUS: And so
what's amazing is--

00:08:47.010 --> 00:08:47.760
SALMAN KHAN: That's
in their liver.

00:08:47.760 --> 00:08:50.370
DAVID AGUS: Colon cancer looks
a certain way, in a lymph node,

00:08:50.370 --> 00:08:52.600
in the liver, on a CAT scan.

00:08:52.600 --> 00:08:54.650
And it always looks that way.

00:08:54.650 --> 00:08:57.060
The body doesn't care what
the underlying genetics are

00:08:57.060 --> 00:08:59.930
because the genetics are
dramatically different patient,

00:08:59.930 --> 00:09:01.400
to patient, to patient.

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:02.729
But it always looks the same.

00:09:02.729 --> 00:09:03.520
SALMAN KHAN: I see.

00:09:03.520 --> 00:09:04.970
DAVID AGUS: So
somehow, evolution

00:09:04.970 --> 00:09:08.810
is selecting out for phenotype,
which is what things look like,

00:09:08.810 --> 00:09:10.570
not necessarily for genotype.

00:09:10.570 --> 00:09:11.250
SALMAN KHAN: Which
is their actual--

00:09:11.250 --> 00:09:12.857
the DNA that makes
up what they are.

00:09:12.857 --> 00:09:13.690
DAVID AGUS: Exactly.

00:09:13.690 --> 00:09:15.405
And so we're
focusing on genotype.

00:09:15.405 --> 00:09:17.840
And genotype is very
important and it's

00:09:17.840 --> 00:09:19.970
going to give us some
understanding over time.

00:09:19.970 --> 00:09:22.880
But we have to also
take that step back

00:09:22.880 --> 00:09:25.510
and look at the phenotype, and
look at what it looks like,

00:09:25.510 --> 00:09:28.000
and try to change
those interactions.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.350
Remember, if a patient
has early cancer,

00:09:30.350 --> 00:09:32.200
we've learned a lot
in the last 10 years.

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:34.110
So if you have early
cancer, and I cure you

00:09:34.110 --> 00:09:36.960
with surgery, the day
before surgery I can always

00:09:36.960 --> 00:09:38.572
find cancer cells
in the blood,--

00:09:38.572 --> 00:09:39.280
SALMAN KHAN: Wow.

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:40.950
DAVID AGUS: --even
though you were cured.

00:09:40.950 --> 00:09:42.320
So the old days,
we thought, well,

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:44.695
you have to wait till it goes
out through our bloodstream

00:09:44.695 --> 00:09:45.860
and gets out there.

00:09:45.860 --> 00:09:47.040
That's wrong.

00:09:47.040 --> 00:09:49.659
It's can it live outside
that original organ?

00:09:49.659 --> 00:09:50.450
SALMAN KHAN: I see.

00:09:50.450 --> 00:09:52.940
So there's someone who's
cured or they're not

00:09:52.940 --> 00:09:54.070
cancering right now.

00:09:54.070 --> 00:09:56.640
And there is actually
cancer in their blood.

00:09:56.640 --> 00:09:59.300
But because they're
healthy now, or healthier,

00:09:59.300 --> 00:10:01.800
or they're healhing, or I guess
however you want to call it,

00:10:01.800 --> 00:10:03.090
that cancer isn't
able to take hold.

00:10:03.090 --> 00:10:03.960
DAVID AGUS: And
those cells, they

00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:05.390
can't live anywhere
but the colon.

00:10:05.390 --> 00:10:05.990
SALMAN KHAN: Fascinating.

00:10:05.990 --> 00:10:07.270
DAVID AGUS: So listen
to this experiment.

00:10:07.270 --> 00:10:08.620
This is the wildest experiment.

00:10:08.620 --> 00:10:09.780
They took a mouse.

00:10:09.780 --> 00:10:12.120
And they took breast
cancer and they put it

00:10:12.120 --> 00:10:14.400
in the left breast
and the right breast.

00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:17.330
And they colored them
red and green, the cells.

00:10:17.330 --> 00:10:19.590
They waited a day,
they went back,

00:10:19.590 --> 00:10:22.130
and the cells were half
red, half green; half red,

00:10:22.130 --> 00:10:23.210
half green.

00:10:23.210 --> 00:10:24.690
Because we always
thought if cancer

00:10:24.690 --> 00:10:27.522
is something in one
local spot, it really

00:10:27.522 --> 00:10:29.730
is a disease that keep going
through the bloodstream.

00:10:29.730 --> 00:10:31.010
And it likes those breasts.

00:10:31.010 --> 00:10:32.720
That's why it keeps
going back there.

00:10:32.720 --> 00:10:33.030
SALMAN KHAN: So interesting.

00:10:33.030 --> 00:10:34.613
And when I always
think of metastases,

00:10:34.613 --> 00:10:36.370
and I can never say
is the word, I always

00:10:36.370 --> 00:10:37.890
imagine it, OK, that's
the cancer that's

00:10:37.890 --> 00:10:39.360
finally gotten to
the lymph network.

00:10:39.360 --> 00:10:41.050
It's finally gotten to the blood
vessels and now it's spreading

00:10:41.050 --> 00:10:42.924
But you're saying that
there's actually often

00:10:42.924 --> 00:10:45.680
cancer that has gotten
to the transportation

00:10:45.680 --> 00:10:46.890
networks of the body.

00:10:46.890 --> 00:10:48.575
But it has still
not metastasized

00:10:48.575 --> 00:10:50.200
because it's not able
to take hold yet.

00:10:50.200 --> 00:10:51.080
DAVID AGUS: Exactly.

00:10:51.080 --> 00:10:51.470
SALMAN KHAN: That's fascinating.

00:10:51.470 --> 00:10:51.880
DAVID AGUS: Exactly.

00:10:51.880 --> 00:10:53.890
And over time, we're going
to get the technology

00:10:53.890 --> 00:10:56.560
to interrogate those cells
to say, hey, this one

00:10:56.560 --> 00:10:57.870
can take hold here.

00:10:57.870 --> 00:11:00.412
Therefore, I have to change
where it would take hold.

00:11:00.412 --> 00:11:02.620
We're just at the beginning
of that technology that's

00:11:02.620 --> 00:11:03.790
going to change everything.

00:11:03.790 --> 00:11:05.331
SALMAN KHAN: And
the reason why we're

00:11:05.331 --> 00:11:07.450
looking at these, the
fact that colon cancer

00:11:07.450 --> 00:11:09.450
starts in the colon and this
is how it looks when it spreads

00:11:09.450 --> 00:11:11.533
to different parts of the
body, what you're saying

00:11:11.533 --> 00:11:16.430
is that we shouldn't maybe
be so fixated on just

00:11:16.430 --> 00:11:19.066
the DNA of colon
cancer because it

00:11:19.066 --> 00:11:21.190
can be very different from
one patient to the next.

00:11:21.190 --> 00:11:23.154
But maybe on kind of
its macrobehavior,

00:11:23.154 --> 00:11:25.070
it's phenotype, how it
looks, and how behaves.

00:11:25.070 --> 00:11:27.980
And that way,
it'll give us clues

00:11:27.980 --> 00:11:29.377
maybe on how we can change it.

00:11:29.377 --> 00:11:30.210
DAVID AGUS: Exactly.

00:11:30.210 --> 00:11:30.910
SALMAN KHAN: Fascinating.

00:11:30.910 --> 00:11:31.430
Thanks a bunch.

00:11:31.430 --> 00:11:32.471
This is very interesting.

00:11:32.471 --> 00:11:33.960
DAVID AGUS: It's great.

